diff:1670110839:1669581652:=70,84d69%0a%3c #foxbegin 221203-234040-788030#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Reflection on the Mexihcah/Aztec Tribe as Presented in Schools %0a%3c -> - yeekitc%0a%3c -> [-03.12.2022 - 15:40-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221203-234040-788030 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The Aztec are arguably one of the more well-known indigenous people of South America. Often, they are introduced in high school world history courses in conjunction with the exploration and subsequent colonization of the Americas by the Europeans. As such, my first formal education about the Aztec came from "State Building in the Americas from c. 1200-1450", a unit in AP World History: Modern. The Aztec were presented then as hunter gatherers who founded Tenochtitlan (now Mexico City) and were technologically advanced for their time when it came to irrigation and their theocratic tribute system. However, they were also presented as a thing of the past: an essentially extinct people whose conquests garnered resentment which was then used for their own conquest by the Spaniards. Due to this, it comes as a surprise that there are still so many speakers of Nahuatl alive today, and that it is still used as a primary language.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221203-234040-788030#%0a
