diff:1669581652:1665168184:=52,69c52%0a%3c #foxbegin 221127-204052-560720#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Nahuatl Revitalization Programs %0a%3c -> - aarnavp%0a%3c -> [-27.11.2022 - 12:40-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221127-204052-560720 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c On the topic of indigenous language reclamation of Nahuatl, the Indigenous Language Institute in Zacatecas, Mexico (IDIEZ) are at the forefront of Nahuatl language revitalization. The two founders – Sabine and Eduardo – make an effort to translating hundreds of Getty Vocabulary entries (an open source arts culture thesaurus) into Nahuatl, providing more means for its education. They note the role of generational decline with the language, where fluent Nahuatl speakers choose to speak Spanish publicly/constrain Nahuatl to home from generational trauma influenced by Mexico’s colonial history. A big effort in their revitalization efforts is to target the small communities of Nahuatl native speakers through modern education programs, preserving the Nahuatl culture while providing access to technology to allow its proliferation amongst native speakers. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1) https://www.getty.edu/news/revitalizing-an-endangered-indigenous-language/%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221127-204052-560720#%0a---%0a> %0a
